{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696386/1930092601/0435.xml":{"full_text":"WASHIiGTOi NEWS BE\nSpectator Advises Traders Stay Out of Market and Wait Developments\nFURTHER BHHISH DRIVES\nPOSSIBLE, HE SIHS\nEncouragement Gathered From Stubborn\nness of Leaders Like Steel, General\nMotors, and American Can;\nTrend Still Downward\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nIf there is any bottom to the market it wasn\u2019t very\napparent yesterday. Stocks cracked again under heavy\nselling in which there was a good deal more liquidation.\nSome encouragement can be found in the stubbomess of\nthe leaders like Steel, General Motors and Can.\nEach still shows a fair clearance above its low for the\nyear, especially Can. They are evidently meeting with\nsome support while the rest of the list is trying to find\nits own level. Yet the trend of the market is still down\nward, and I wouldn\u2019t advise trying to guess the day-to-day\nsellings.\nStay out of the market until there is some indication\nstock prices are near stabilization.\nThe Seiling\nThere is no question that there\nis real liquidation in stocks.\nAction of two groups, the oils\nand motors yesterday, indicated\nthis in the liberal number of new\nlows in these sections of the list.\nTired-but holders are getting\nout, influenced by the likelihood\nthat either the automobile Aior\nthe petroleum companies are\ngoing to get anywhere this year.\nSelling in the oils also wa due\nto the continued unsettlement ifi\nthe crude oil production and re\nfining ends.\nDespite th?, heroic efforts of\npetroleum lea u?\u00bb s, the lid\nthreatens to blow off at almost\nany time. I am told that\nconsiderable investment trust\nselling is taking 'lace, too. Some\ntrusts are being forced to sell\nk to improve their financial posi\ntions. I hear, while others are\n.liquidating the dubious looking\nstocks in their portfolios.\nWhen you add to this selling\nthe powerful bear pressure, the\nbreak becomes an oper book.\nThere is no do.bt that the bear\nforces ..re well organized while\nthe bul are running hither and\nthither. The suspicion wont\ndown that son: of the recent bull\nleaders have been operating on\nr the short side. Which isn\u2019t sur\nprising, since floor traders are he\nfirst to switch when they sense\na change. The good stocks are\nbeing ell bought but only a\nscale down.\nChrysler\nChrysler was one to make a\nnew low for the year. Insiders,\nhowever, are still bullish on the\ncompany\u2019s long-term outlook and\nare taking all the stock offered on\n5 the way down. There was no real\nattempt to hold Chrysler* at its\nlow for the year, since the senti\nmental value attached to this sup\nport would be less on the general\nmarket morale than holding, say,\nCan or Steel above their lows.\nChrysler won\u2019t make much\nmoney this year. The stock, how\never, is now selling about $9 a\nshare below its book value. Those\nclose to the company aren\u2019t giv\ning any thought to dividend ac-\ntion. It looks as though the divi\ndend will be cut, though the rate\ncould easily be continued since\nChrysler in its last statement\nshowed about $50,000,000 in cash\nk and investments. Even if pay\nment on the common were\nomitted entirely, the stock would\nseem to have discounted almost\neverything when you consider\nwhere other nondividend paying\nstock with less behind them are\nselling currently.\nAmerican Water Works con\ntinues the bright spot in the\nutility list, showing a big clear\nance above its low. Rumor\nf won\u2019t down that there is some\ndeal coming. Standard Gas\nwants Water Works, but says there\nis nothing in the wind now. I am\ntold Commonwealth and South-\nWEST VIRGINIA\nGAS SALES UP\nWest Virginia Gas Corporation,\nmost recently acquired subsidiary\nof Appalachian Gas Corporation,\nsold 2,639,281,000 cubic feet of\nnatural gas during the first seven\nmonths of this year, according\nto statement of the parent com\npany.\nAcquisition of West Virginia\nGas Corporation in July marked\nthe sixth subsidiary and the\neighth company to come within\nthe scope of Appalachian Gas\nCorporation group in less than\na five-month period.\nThe 127 wells,of the West Vir\nginia Gas Corporation are lo\ncated on the company\u2019s leases in\nr Southern West Virginia, compris\ning approximately 52,209 acres.\nOutput of natural gas is sold un\nder long term contracts to United\nFuel Gas Company, subsidiary of\nColumbia Gas and Electric Cor\nporation; Owens-IPinois chn\u00ab\nCompany, Columbian Carbon\nCompany and International i\nNickel Company.\nem has its eye on Water Works,\ntoo. However, I don\u2019t advise a\u00aby\ncommitments now.\nRadio\nRadio went in to new low\nground for the year and another\nromance went up tn smoke. It\nhad been well said that Radio had\nbeen selling at fiction prices, the\nstory in this case being the long\nrange view of the industry and\nits tremendous possibility tor ex\npansion in the next few years.\nThe possibility still exists what\never price Radio is driven to in\nthis reaction. Everyone knows\nthat Radio isn\u2019t going to make\nany money this year.\nPrecipitate break of the pre\nferred B indicates some alarm\nabout the dividend on this stock.\nThe bears in the past have paid\nthrough the nose oh Radio. It now\nseems they are getting some of it\nback. Incidentally, a leading bear\ntrader was credited with the pre\ndiction that Radio would go to\n$5 a share. This was later denied.\nHowever, at 5 almost everyone\nwould probably buy a share of the\nstock, frame it and put it over\nthe radio at home to have some\nthing to berate when all you get\nis a lot of static. And at 10, too.\nRadio to me would look like a buy\naround 25 for its speculative ap\npeal alone.\nSoftness in Standard Brands\nhas again raised the question of\nthe safety of its $1.50 dividend.\nAt current prices the stock\nyields about B\u20192 per cent. In\nterests close to the management\nstill insist that the dividend will\nbe maintained this year, as de\nclared here recently. The\nFleischmanns, I am told, are all\nfor it, while nothing is known of\nany change in the Morgan atti\ntude.\nHere and There\nImpressive action of American\nCan would seem to indicate the\nlikelihood of some action on an\nextra dividend at Tuesday\u2019s meet\ning of the directors. The stock is\ncertainly being well bought, and\nby well-informed sources, too.\nThere is no doubt that there\nhas been inside buying in many\nstocks in the past few years, if\nfor no other reason than to main\ntain an orderly market. Stocks\nlike International Harvester and\nAmerican Smelting Indicate this.\nThere has been little outside buy\ning in 'even the best of stocks.\nIt looks as though the bears are\nafter Gillette again.\nThere has been smart selling\nin Vanadium by those who ex\npect to see it go much lower.\nWeakness in United Aircraft is\nlinked with the break in Vana\ndium. There is said to have been\none crowd working in both.\nThere has been good selling in\nKroger due to the general market\nunsettlement. I am told much of\nthis is profit-taking on speculative\nstock bought lower down. In-\nI siders, however, are still said to\nbe bullish on the company\u2019s long\nterm prospects.\nPENNEVLISTS\nARE CUT\nInventories of J. C. Penney\nCompany as of August 31, 1930,\nwere substantially lower than\nthose on the company\u2019s books Au\ngust 31, 1929. Store inventories\naggregated $45,017,000 against\n$46,346,000 on August 31, 1929, a\ndecrease of $1,329:000 in spite of\nthe fact that there were 148 more\nstores in operation August 31 Os\nthis \u2019year.\nWarehouse inventories of $12,-\n464,000 compared with $13,506,000,\na decrease of $1,042,000. Com\nbined reduction in store and ware\nhouse inventories as of August 31/\n1930, was $2,371,000.\nAverage inventory per store Au\ngust 31, 1930, based on 1,440 stores\nwas approximately $31,000 against\n$36,000 per store on 1,292 stores\nin operation a year previously, a\nreduction of $5,000. Warehouse\ninventory per store August 31. 1930\nwas approximately $9,000 on 1,-\n440 stores against SIO,OOO a store\non 1.292 stores August 31. 1929,\na reduction of SI,OOO. A\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nPresides\nJr \u25a0\"A\na\nMEL...\nK\u00bbL,.\nA\n\u2014Staff Photo\nMABEL V. ROYCE\nOF THE Washington Loan\nand Trust Company, who pre\nsided at the meeting of the\nWashington Bank Women\u2019s\nClub last night at the Huguenot.\nREPORT CUTTEN\nWHEAT PROFIT\nWhile the Russian government\nhas cleaned up around $400,000\nselling grain short in the Chicago\nmarket, the big American opera\ntors have been making a killing\nof several millions on the bear\nside, it was learned today.\nArthur W. Cutten, largest indi\nvidual trader in grain, is reported\nto have made $25,000,000 in the\nChicago Board of Trade\u2019s wheat\npit this year.\nWheat\u2019s Slump\nWheat this year has fallen from\nabove $1.25 a bushel to around 80\ncents a bushel now.\nCompared to the profit of the\nbear speculators, the Federal\nBoard, with, its 60,000,000 bushels\nof wheat bought at an average\nprice of $1.25 a bushel, has a paper\nloss of $27,000,000.\nCutten learned the technique of\nthe grain market as bookkeeper to\nthe president of the Chicago Board\nof Trade, A. S. Whiteback, in 1897.\nWithin 10 years he was a million\naire.\nBack in 1925 he cleaned up $14,-\n000,000 in reported operations in\nwheat and rye. The year before\nhe was reported to have netted\naround $2,000,000 in com.\nCash Operations\nCutten's boast is that his grain\noperations are usually in cash. He\nhas not always been on the win\nning side, though back in 1922 he\nwas nipped for a fortune in \"the\nMay ;queeze\u201d in wheat.\nIn the bull stock market of the\nlast five .'ears Cutten was one of\nthe big 10 traders whose combined\nprofits at one time were placed at\n$500,000,000.\nHis most prominent stock opera\ntions were in Montgomery Ward,\nBaldwin, Loose Wiles Biscuit and\nUnipn Carbide.\nCutten is a Canadian by birth.\nIn the market crash of last year\nthe citizens of his birthplace\u2014\nGuelph, Ontario, are reported to\nhave dropped $3,000,000. The resi\ndents of Guelph were in the habit\nof plunging when Cutten did. He\nhas spent millions in improving\nthe town.\nBank Women Hear\nMiss Alice Whitton\nMiss Alice Whitton, of the First\nNational Bank of Alexandria. Va..\naddressed the dinner meeting of\nthe Washington Bank Women\u2019s\nClub at the Huguenot last night.\nShe described her recent trip\nabroad. Miss Mabel V, Royce, of\nthe Washington Loan and Trust\nCompany, presided.\nLoans to Brokers\nRemain Unchanged\nNEW YORK. Sept. 26 (1.N.5.).\nBrokers\u2019 loans were unchanged in\nthe week ended September 24,\naccording to the weekly report of\nthe Federal Reserve Board. The\npresent total of $3,222,000,000\ncompares with $6,761,000,000 on\nSeptember 25, 1929.\nFenner Beane\nNew York New Orleans\nMembers New York Stock\nExchange f.nd other\norincipal exchanges\nWashington Office:\n1430 K Street N. W.\nTel. National 4933\nI\nZimmerman Urges\nSupply Purchases to\nAid Business Trend\nThe best way to restore public\ni confidence in business and bring\ni about a prompt revival of trade\nin all lines is for large purchasers\nto go into the market and buy\nnow, John E. Zimmermann, presi\ndent of the United Gas Improve\nment Co., declared today. Busi\nness conditions and prices,\nMr. Zimmermann believes, have\nreached the turning point up\njward, which will make purchases\nat a later date less favorable.\n'Supporting this belief he has\naddressed a letter tp the local\nmanagement of all U. G. I. sub\nsidiary companies in which he\nsuggests that they at once antici\npate their normal requirements\nfor several months and place\norders.\nBusiness Is Sound\n\u201cIt is felt that the purchase\nof materials can be made ad\nvantageously at thia time,\u201d he\nsaid, \u201cand that improvements\nin business conditions may make\nlater purchases less favorable.\nBusiness conditions in this\ncountry are essentially sound,\nand I look for a steady and\ngradual improvement.\u201d\nUnited Gas Improvement is the\nsecond of the large utility com\npanies to announce making pur\nchases at the present time.\nWestern Electric recently an\nnounced that in view of the pre\nvailing low level of copper prices,\nit was buying in comparatively\nlarge quantities.\nFrom Cleveland another note\nof optimism is struck by Dr.\nDavid Friday, economist, who in\nan address before the Cleveland\nChamber of Commerce, forecasts\na sure but slow recovery in busi\nness for the remainder of the\nyear and a decided improvement\nin 1931 with 1932 probably an\nother record year.\nDr. Friday pointed out in that\nin August of 1921 the Federal\nReserve business index stood at\naround 64 from which it rose to\n71 in January of 1922. He ex\npect*, he said, an increase of that\nproportion for the balance of the\npresent year.\nIn his address Dr. Friday\nstressed seven points that he con\nsidered pertinent in the business\noutlook. They are:\nRaw material prices have prob\nably, reached their low levels and\nany change will be somewhat up\nwards. The same applies to farm\nproducts.\nFinished Prices Stabilized\nPrices for finished materials\nare about stabilized. There might\nDirector\nni\n\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nDANIEL WILLARD\nPRESIDENT OF the Balti\nmore and Ohio Railroad who\nhas been authorized by the\nInterstate Commerce Commis\nsion to serve as a director of\nthe Buffalo and Susquehanna\nRailroad.\nW. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stock Exchange House\nHaving Its Main Office in Washington\n_MEM BE RS\u2014\u2014\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nJ New York Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade\nAmerican Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nHIBBS BUILDING.\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. C.\nr.\nTA\u00ab National Daily\nbe some slight readjustment with\na possibility of minor decreases.\nWages will remain at their\npresent level. If there is any\nchange it will be downward very\nslightly.\nDividends in 1931 will be less\nthan 10 per cent under the 1930\nlevel and higher than any pre\nvious year.\nInterest rates will remain low\nuntil next summer.\nBond prices will continue up\nfor the next, six months.\nBusiness is now on a modest\nupward trend. There will be an\naccelerated pickup later in the\nfall. The year 1931 will continue\nto show Improvement and 1932\nwill probably be another record\nyear.\nManaging Director Clapp of\nthe National Electric Light Asso\nciation, says conditions in the\nelectric light and power industry\nare favorable and the outlook for\nan upward trend in output in\nelectric power is excellent.\nUNITED CRH\nON LIST\nListing of 271.000 shares of\ncommon stock of the United Elec\ntric Coal Company, to replace the\ntrust certificates for common\nstock, was approved by the gov\nerning oemmittee of. the New\nYork Stock Exchange.\nOther securities to be listed on\nnotice of their issuance were:\nAuburn Automobile Company\u2014\n-3.690 additional shares of com\nmon capital stock without nom\ninal or par value.\nComfhercial Investment Trust\nCorporation 33,673 additional\nshares of common stock without\nnominal or par value.\nNorth American Company\u2014\n-150,469 additional shares of com\nmon stock without nominal or par\nvalue.\nUtilities Power and Light Cor\nporation\u20143s,ooo additional shares\nof Class A stock without nominal\nor par value.\nUnited States Steel Corpora\ntion\u201422s,79o additional shares of\ncommon stock. SIOO par value.\nCommercial Solvents Coipora\ntion \u201449,670 shares of common\nstock without nominal or par\nvalue.\nCanadian Pacific Railway Com\npany\u2014l3,4oo,ooo shares of ordi\nnary capital stock, $25 par value.\nPhiladelphia Company\u2014loo,ooo\nshares of $6 cumulative prefer\nence stock without nominal or par\nvalue.\nCanadian National Railway\nCompany\u2014sso,ooo,ooo 25-year 4%\nper cent guaranteed gold oonds,\ndue June 15, 1955.\nNew Diamond Match\nStock to Be Listed\nThe governing committee of\nthe New York Stock Exchange has\napproved the application of the\nDiamond Match Company for the\nlisting of certificates of deposit\nfor 170.000 shares to be issued\nunder the company's plan of re\nincorporation and recapitaliza\ntion.\nApplication for the listing of\nthe Celotex Company was ap\nproved, as was the listing of cer\ntificates of deposit for 284,552\nshares of preferred stock and\n333,221 of common stock of the\nAmerican Agriculture and Chemi\ncal Company, under the reor\nganization plan announced re\ncently by the reorganization com\nmittee.\nCoal Rafas Flayed\nIn New Hampshire\nCONCORD, N. H.. Sept. 26\n(IJJJ.S.). \u2014Claiming that indus\ntries in the State are suffering\nfrom unreasonable and discrimi\nnatory railroad freight rates on\ncoal shipped from the Penn\nsylvania and West Virginia fields,\nattorneys for the State of New\nHampshire prepared a reduced\nfreight Yate schedule for presenta\ntion to the Interstate Commerce\nCommission.\nth i DAY, sexreMaeN re, 1h\u00bbO\nBrooklyn Savings\nBanks to Merge\nPlans for the consolidation of\nthe Lincoln Savings Bank and the\nChurch Lane Savings Bank, both\nof Brooklyn, have been completed,\nit was announced today. The\nname of the former bank will be\nused as the name of the combined\ninstitutions.\nThe jnerged banks will rank as\nthe third largest savings bank in\nBrooklyn and will have total re\nsources of $104,500,000, of which\nthe Lincoln Bank will contribute\n$102,000,000 and the Church Lane\n$2,500,000. The Lincoln Savings\nBank is one of the oldest in Brook\nlyn, having been organized about\n65 years ago.\nWHAT INVESTMENT IN HEARST CONSOLIDATED PUBLICATIONS SECURES\nPreference plus\nParticipation\n...the protection of (1) a preferred\nposition as to an ownership interest\nin assets and (2) a prior call on 7%\ndividends, together with a substantial\nsharing.. .up to an extra 3%.. .in the\nultimate additional earnings that accrue\nto the common stock.\nin short, fixed-income assurance\nI\nand security, and a ratable participation\nin profits as realized in extra dividends.\n\nThese are the advantages and benefits\nenjoyed by the purchasers of\nHearst Consolidated Publications, Inc.\n7% Cumulative Participating Class A Stock\nPreferred as to Assets and Dividends\n\nThis consolidated corporation has acquired eleven\nof the strongest and most profitable metropolitan\npublications owned by William Randolph Hearst:\nNET PAID CIRCULATION\nas of March 31, 1930\nEstablished Daily Sunday The American\nNew York Evening Journall\u00df96- 630,368 Weekly\nChicago Evening American 1900- 569,167\nPittsburgh Sun-Telegraph 1841-1906 178,192 352,362 352,362\nDetroit Times 1900 274,464 381,706 381,706\nSan Francisco Examiner 1880 187,031 387,034 387,034\nSan Francisco Call-8u11etin...1856-1871 124,338\nOakland Post-Enquirer 1886 57,872\nLos Angeles Examiner 1903 457,317 457,317\nLos Angeles Evening Herald 1911\nSeattle Post-Intelligencer 1865 104, <~4 16a,598 165,598\nThe American Weekly, additional. .1882 3,86.,226\nTOTAL CIRCULATION... 2,563,426 1,744,017 5,6Q6,243\nTheir tremendous, established, earning power is\nindicated in the following consolidated figures of\nthe Certified Public Accountants:\nEARNINGS Dividend Requirements\n(after depreciation, interest and o f class A stock offered for sale\nFederal Income Tax)\nAmount Times Earned\n1926 $10,009,806 $3,500,000 2.86\n1927 10,162,284 3,500,000 2.90\n1928 11,044,777 3,500,000 3.15\n1929 12,854,626 3,500,000 3.67\nAverage $11,017,873 $3,500,000 3.14\nPrice $25 a Share\nPlus Accrued Dividend\nX\nHearst Consolidated Publications, Inc.\nFill in the coupon for details\u2014no obligation\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES CO.,\n.\u2014a k. Stock Sales Department\nSubscriptions to thu stoc unll 1317-21 R N w Washington( D> c\nreceived at The Washington Times\n1 1317-31 H* Street N. W., Waih- Kindly send full details about Hearst Consolidated Pub-\nlications, Inc., 7% shares.\ningtonf D. C, business office, Stock\nSales Department, or at the cashier\u2019s\noffice of any Hearst newspaper or Name\ncorporation in the United States.\nAddress\nl 1 i h\nA. T, T. Applies\nFor Stock Listing\nApplication by the American\nTelephone and Telegraph Com\npany to list 150,000 additional\nshares of its capital stock on the\nNew York Stock Exchange re\nveals that the company as of\nAugust 31 last had $1,762,947,000\nof capital stock outstanding. With\nthe present issue which is to be\nused in acquiring the Teletype\nCorporation, the total shares out\nstanding will be within 1.396,338\nshares of the amount authorized.\nIt is expected that a stockhold\ners meeting will be called shortly\nto authorize an increase in the\npresent 20,000,000 shares of capi\ntal stock to some larger figure.\nNational Dairy Gets\nN. J. Ice Cream FirrrU\nThe National Dairy Products'\nCorporation has acquired the en\ntire assets and properties of the\nJersey Ice Cream Company, it\nwas disclosed in the former com\npany\u2019s application to the New\nYork Stock Exchange to list\n4,486 additional shares of its\nstock.\nThe additional stock is to be\u2019\u2019\niced as partis? payment for the\nice cream company, the ba\u2019ance\nbeing the assumption of the lia\nbilities. and the delivery of S7O\n000 aggregate principal amount\nof itk s\u00a5\u00ab per cent gold deben\ntures.\n29","height":"30387","width":"24252"}}
